

# Webserver Cluster Module

A reusable Terraform module that provisions a highly available web server cluster on AWS. It uses an **Auto Scaling Group (ASG)** to manage instances and an **Application Load Balancer (ALB)** to distribute traffic across them.



## Usage

hcl
module "webserver_cluster" {
  source = "../../modules/services/webserver-cluster"

  cluster_name  = "webservers-dev"
  instance_type = "t3.micro"
  min_size      = 2
  max_size      = 4
}




## Inputs Explained

This module requires a few key variables to control how the infrastructure is deployed.

 **cluster_name**
  This is the name prefix used for all resources created by the module. It helps identify and group related resources in AWS. This value must be provided.

 **instance_type**
  Defines the EC2 instance type used in the Auto Scaling Group. If not specified, it defaults to `t3.micro`, which is suitable for development or low-traffic environments.

 **min_size**
  The minimum number of EC2 instances that should always be running in the Auto Scaling Group. This ensures availability even during low traffic.

 **max_size**
  The maximum number of instances the Auto Scaling Group can scale up to during high demand.

 **server_port**
  The port on which the web server listens. By default, this is set to port 80 for standard HTTP traffic.
 **ami**
  The Amazon Machine Image (AMI) used to launch instances. A default AMI is provided, but this can be overridden if needed.

 **region**
  Specifies the AWS region where resources will be deployed. If not set, it defaults to `eu-north-1`.

---

## Outputs Explained

After deployment, the module exposes several outputs that are useful for accessing and integrating the infrastructure.

 **alb_dns_name**
  This is the public DNS name of the Application Load Balancer. It is the main endpoint used to access the web application.

 **asg_name**
  The name of the Auto Scaling Group managing the EC2 instances. This is useful for monitoring and scaling operations.

**alb_arn**
  The Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the load balancer. This can be used when integrating with other AWS services or for advanced configurations.

